text.text: A Guide to Bermondsey

text.html: Cobbled streets, Victorian pubs and proximity to the Thames combine to make Bermondsey a quaint and delightful slice of historic London. It’s somewhat of a wonder how such a lovely corner of the city can be located so centrally and yet remain pretty peaceful and removed from the true hustle and bustle of the metropolis. We like wonders so we went on a wander and found ourselves having it large at Berm-on-Sea. Fancy that.

Best for… your morning coffee and pastry

tip.text:
A Grade II listed building (and for good reason), this old watch house was originally designed to house the guards of the neighbouring church but has now been converted into one of the cosiest cafes in town. Yes, space is limited, but the interior is absolutely stunning and there's no shortage on goodies on offer.

Sandwiches, crumpets and salads all accompany the fantastic coffee and make this a perfect spot for a cosy pitstop when out in Bermondsey, just be ready for the pre-work and lunchtime coffee rushes - they get pretty nuts so we'd suggest being in or out before it all kicks off.

text.text: Definitely the place to grab your AM coffee or indulge in a spot of remote working on Bermondsey St, The Watch House is a beautiful conversion of an old churchyard watch house. It’s a tiny space and can get pretty hot, but this listed building and cute cafe is a true London rarity. Appreciate the interior design while you chomp on a pastry from Borough Market or pick up a freshly made panini on the move - whatever tickles your tum.
Best for… your morning pint (if that’s how you roll)

tip.text:
The sense of history in here is tangible: maybe it's Frank, the old licensee and pint-puller, or maybe it's all the dark wood and black and white photos. Either way, this pub has been knocking around since 1890 and that's a pretty long time. Don't be surprised to find friendly and personable chaps drinking pints, reading and listening to classical music at 11am on a weekday.

With an average pint price of £3.80 and some decent real ales on tap, The Royal Oak is a fair shout for an inexpensive beer in relatively central London. Didn't bring anything to read? Don't fret, there's a Royal British Legion book sale by the bar.

text.html: There’s something kind of warming about the sight of three sixty-plus gents enjoying a spot of classical music and a cheeky read with their first beer of the day. Camaraderie is a fine thing, as is a real, no frills boozer like this one here. The Royal Oak will be sure to get some real ales down your windpipe, while you can expect conversation amongst regulars to be rife and engaging - come down on your own but don’t expect to sit in silence.

Best for... good value fresh pasta

tip.text:
Pasta and wine - it's a killer combo of creamy carbs, washed down with a glass of fine vino. What else is there in this dreary world? Enter Flour & Grape; they're not reinventing the wheel but they are hand rolling some mighty good fresh pasta. Tortellini with roasted pork shoulder and sage butter? Yes we will. Beetroot ravioli with walnut butter? Er... could you just give us a minute? **Heavy slurping sounds.**

And if you're left with an insatiable dairy craving and half a bottle of red? The Italian cheese board it is. Who needs inspiring conversation or attractive company when you've got cheese. Right guys?

Best for... cocktails with a conscience

tip.text:
Take one step into Nine Lives and you’re a million miles away from the hustle of London Bridge. From dark wood features and palm fronds to a vintage sound system and layers of incense, every detail has been carefully planned to create that elusive feeling of escapism. But that's not all this cocktail bar is up to. It's also making lots of noise on the sustainability train, with low waste cocktails, low plastic usage, up-cycled furniture and a herb garden out back (run by St Mungo's homeless charity no less).

And the results for your drinking pleasure? Sweet treats like the Kelross Daiquiri which replaces limes with relatively local Bramley apples; and the Kafé Kerna,l a non-alcoholic, bitter coffee number. If you've a more classical flavour palate, order the (off menu) Lutra which fills your mouth beautifully with Tanqueray, sake, dry white wine, lemon, sugar and creme de peche. At £9.50 you'd be hard pressed to find better in these ends.

Best for... homestyle Italian cooking

tip.text:
Traditional Italian cooking just like their grandmas used to make it: if that doesn't get you salivating then you've got psychological issues that need addressing. Fine Foods started off as a deli, serving the good people of Bermondsey authentic charcuterie, cheeses and pasta sauces. So popular was this that they decided to venture into dining services proper.

The likes of ragu bolognese, fish & octopus stew and delightful roasted sausages with polenta all feature here, cooked with fresh, seasonal ingredients. In a bit of a rush? Chill, grab yourself a banging sandwich and get going!

Best for… a romantic rendez-vous

tip.text:
Is this what Ernest Hemingway had in mind when he declared Paris a moveable feast? Probably not, but Bermondsey’s cosy Casse-Croute feels like it’s upped and moved completely - from the tablecloths to the sommelier, Alex, it’s easy to forget that you’re in London. The menu is different every day, but recurring classics include coq au vin and rabbit in mustard sauce with mashed potatoes.

If you’re feeling parched then treat yourself to a glass (or bottle) of fine French wine. They’ve only got one beer on tap, ‘Pression’ (literally 'beer on tap' in French), but then again it is brewed especially for them. How cute.

It’s small and popular, so be sure to book ahead.

text.text: Bermondsey is full of treats but we reckon this is the pick of the bunch. Casse Croute is a portal that will transport you to 1950s Paris: vintage signs, antique trinkets, black and white photos and a resident sommelier. Yeah, that’s a french wine expert, and yes he does have glorious facial hair. The menu in here changes on the daily and the French wine list is as impressive as they come - don’t think you’re above booking ahead though ‘cos this spot is very small and very popular. Do the math.
Best for… a sophisticated glass of beer

tip.text:
Wood, brass, gold, mirrors, chandeliers; must be France. Right? Wrong. Bermondsey's The Rose has been spruced up and turned into a wonderfully classy and smooth gastropub, all antique furniture and craft beer. The soundtrack is jazzy and relaxing while the staff are friendly and welcoming.

These guys care about serving stellar beers, so expect the best of London's offerings, with the likes of Beavertown's Neck Oil and Hiver's Honey Beer on draught. For your tum The Rose are offering seasonal English food with a French twist - grab the surprise 5 course chef's tasting menu (£36) or something off the a la carte - lamb's neck and dried fruitanyone?

text.text: This quaint gastropub is all kinds of pleasant. This is not where you go to get shit-faced with the boyz or smash out a cheeky game of pool. Far from it. This is where you go when you’re after something a bit classy, maybe a spot of lunch even; a beautifully furnished space ideal for wetting your beak in, so grab a tasty pint of London-brewed craft beer, perch on an antique bench and let that smooth, jazzy soundtrack sweep you away.
Best for… stocking up on bitcoins and caffeine

tip.text:
If you hadn't already guessed from the name, Fuckoffee disregard the status quo. And it's great.

It's got an extravagant coffee menu - including the Fat Wife (Flat White), Shit Storm and the Builders. For you health nuts, they've got some freshly blended fruit smoothies on offer too. It's all very communal; you'll tuck into your slice of cake on a sofa with others and afterwards you can buy a Fuckoffee mug to remember your rebellious caffeinated experience.

text.text: The music is loud, the name is atypical and coffee beans are exclusively sourced from Papa New Guinea: is this a gimmick-y, ‘hipster’ coffee shop? Kind of. Is it funny nonetheless? Definitely. Fuckoffee caused a bit of local uproar when it came onto the scene, and they’ve even framed the letter they received from the council arguing a cause for name-change - go read it, it’s hilarious.
Best for… getting drunk in the proximity of priceless antiques

tip.text:
Wander through this museum-like vintage and salvaged furniture store and discover everything from pillows made from recycled coffee bags, to antique store lettering, old flags, antique maps, old theatre chairs, and every piece of clutter in the book. It's certainly a pricey affair, but you'll be happy to know there are smaller items around the £10-50 marker.

Hidden away in amongst the salvage is a bar and restaurant space too. Serving modern European food and cocktails that pack a punch - using fresh ingredients from the market. The best bit is you can make like eccentric old Miss Havisham and eat-in amongst the treasures.

Restaurant hours: Wednesday to Saturday from 5pm - 10pm, and Sunday 11am - 5pm by booking.

text.text: We walked around in here for ages trying to come to terms with the concept. We reckon we figured it out: it’s an antique salvage yard, everything you see is for sale (except the glorious back bar), but it’s also a dining room and incredible, adventurous cocktail bar. This spot is so singular and so worth checking out - go back a second time and it might look completely different! Marvel at the stuff inside the venue or the stuff the venue’s putting inside you: either way you’ll be amazed.
Best for... casual tacos and frozen margaritas

tip.text:
El Pastor seems to have cracked the formula: vibey, industrial canteen-style dining; delicious, crisp tortillas cooked in-house; and thigh-spankingly tasty fillings that leave your lips glistening. Having finessed this set-up at their inaugural spot in Borough, they've moved their bustling flavours to a disused railway arch in Bermondsey.

We took our cute little tushies and tucked into their infamous taco al pastόr - loaded with slithers of smokey marinated pork shoulder, and complemented by sweet chunks of caramelised pineapple and sprinkles of finely sliced onions and chopped coriander. The chicken number also stood out, with tasty morsels of chicken coated in chipotle and cumin and accompanied by a refreshing salsa taquero. We washed all this down with a couple of frozen margaritas that were teeth-chatteringly cold and whacked our drowsy, overly-stuffed faces with a wicked tequila slap.

text.text: El Pastor seems to have cracked the formula: vibey, industrial canteen-style dining; delicious, crisp tortillas cooked in-house; and thigh-spankingly tasty fillings that leave your lips glistening. If you come here, you ought to sample their infamous taco al pastόr - loaded with slithers of smokey marinated pork shoulder, and complemented by sweet chunks of caramelised pineapple and sprinkles of finely sliced onions and chopped coriander. Throw in some frozen margaritas and what you have is one wild sensory trip.
Best for... Saturday mooching

tip.text:
This bustling weekend market is the beating heart of Bermondsey, the place to come if you like the taste, smell or look of delicious food. It's kinda mad how many different amazing food stalls they manage to cram into this teeny passage - from jerk to gyoza to waffles, they've got it all - not to mention the permanent shops along the opposite side which feature a branch of St. John and one of our favourite tapas spots in the city, Bar Tozino.

The whole thing is shadowed by dozens of huge flags, bunting and the Shard, which makes for a real 'Pride of London' vibe. Unsurprisingly the place is heaving whenever it's open, so you'll have to just tolerate the crowds - especially when everyone is doing at least two laps to scope out all the offerings.

Best for... gazing at those white walls

tip.text:
A stunning piece of modernist industrial architecture on the outside, and the embodiment of the ubiquitous white-walled gallery space on the in, White Cube is as good a place as any to catch some of that contemporary stuff in the Big Smoke.

The original White Cube Gallery gained a reputation in the 90s by giving one person shows to many of the rising YBAs, its name growing alongside those of Tracey Emin and Damien Hirst. Today it continues to host a range of conceptual, boundary-pushing shows across its two London galleries. The Bermondsey branch is the perfect size for an afternoon mooch: it's got three decent spaces, but it's not so big that you feel rushed or knackered by the end. It's also free, which is our favourite price for art (and most things for that matter).
